title: For Sale:  Nice Old Commie Gun in Good Condition **FEG AP~MBP .32acp** Great for Conceal Carry
postcontent: I have a few of these .The FEG AP~MBP is a pistol very similar to the PA-63 except in 7.65mm instead of 9x18 Makarov. This model firearm was used in Hungary during the communist era as a government issued firearm. My understanding is that they were issued by the Hungarian Police and security services (How do you say KGB in Hungarian?) from 1950 to 1957. The FEG AP is very similar to the German Walther PP but the design has been slightly modified by FEG. It features an aluminum frame. It holds 8 rounds of 7.65mm Browning in the magazine. It has a safety decocker lever and is a traditional double action firearm. The double action pull is very long and heavy. The gun weighs in at approximately 20 ounces.  I just received a few of these in from my supplier.  They were supposed to come with 2 mags, but low and behold there was only 1 mag with each.  If my supplier provides the missing extra mags, I will include 1 each with the sale.  These clearly haven't been cleaned after being in long term storage, but they should clean up well.  Grips are all good.  Mechanically they appear to be in excellent condition.  Great classic conceal carry pistol.  I have some .32acp available for local sale.  FEG made some great pistols, and this is one of them.

title: For Sale:  Henry H018-410 Lever Action Shotgun
postcontent: Continuing on with our outside-the-box expansion program, we’re taking our lever actions in another new direction for Henry Repeating Arms with the 2017 introduction of two .410 bore shotguns for those who like their small-gauge shotgunning to be done through a quick-handling platform they’re familiar with in rimfire and centerfire versions already used in the field. If you know our lever actions, you’ll be right at home with these new small-game-getters. There are times and places where a 20 or a 12 is just too much gun, and for those times and places the .410 may be the ideal way to go. Both model variants are based on our blued steel-framed .45-70 Lever Action, with five-shot tube-loading magazines chambered for 2.5” shells only, dark straight-grained American walnut furniture, pistol grip wrists, checkering fore and aft, sling swivel studs, and a good thick non-slip ventilated black rubber recoil pad at the rear. We give you two approaches in this .410. You can be the judge of which best fits your own hunting style. The H018-410 is the long version, with a 24″ round blued barrel, removable factory installed invector style full choke and large front brass bead, with no rear sight. This one provides slightly longer practical ranges with its barrel length, along with additional choke options you can buy separately. The H018-410R is a more versatile and compact package featuring a 20″ barrel, with a cylinder bore “choke”, simply a tapered constriction of the gun barrel’s bore at the muzzle end, and our standard adjustable semi-buckhorn rear and vertical blade bead front sights. The weight’s easier to tote over a long afternoon on foot, with the shorter round barrel working easier through brush and other tight terrain where shots are expected to be close and fast.  The adjustable sights make it easy to regulate patterns with a variety of birdshot and slugs to handle anything from small game birds such as partridge and pigeons through cottontails to fox and coyotes, varmints and pest control. Whether you’re in the camp that regards the .410 as a beginner’s gauge or the camp that considers it a specialist’s gauge, we’ve got you covered with these two new models; simplistic, rugged and a great forager for survival, they’ll fit right in among your other prized Henry lever actions. title: For Sale:  Stock Refinishing
postcontent: I am a professional stockmaker offering to refinish wood stocks. I have been making and finishing stocks for a high-end company for three years. My company does not take low-end jobs, so I am offering a service for regular firearms owners to refinish their rifle stocks or shotgun stock sets. The stocks I make on a daily basis sell for $5,000 just for a shotgun restock, and $8,500 for a rifle build. When I refinish stocks, they come out looking far better than when they came from the factory. The service I am offering entails:-Taping off of chequering-Removal of old finish-Raising of dents and scratches-Repair of cracks-Filling of small holes-Sanding of stock to a 320 grit finish-Filling of pores and grain-Final wet sanding to 600 grit-Lustrous, hand-rubbed tung oil finish-Cleaning up of chequering-Final wax coat to protect finish-Polishing, buffing, or satinizing to desired level of glossThis service will cost a minimum of $500 at the company I work for, and will change hands from employee to employee. I am offering an introductory price of $200 for my personal service. No hands other than mine shall touch the stock throughout the entire process, so no steps will be missed or done out of order. I am am working from my personal shop, and not an FFL, so I will not take in any actions or other pieces. I will only take in your stock or stock set. I am willing to meet to pick it up and drop it off. Estimated turn around time is one week.Why refinish your stock? Most companies use spray on finishes that hide the natural beauty of the wood. They tend to stain it a reddish color, dulling the hues and figure. The finishes they use are designed for maximum profit. Quick and easy to apply, fast drying, and ready to go out the door in a day or two. They also hide the compression marks left in the grain by rasps and files, and sanding scratches left by poor craftsmen. I take the stock down to bare wood and hand rub in penetrating tung oil, which soaks into the wood rather than building up on top of it. You can't hide poor sanding with tung oil. Only after the finish has achieved the desired luster, and popped the figure to its fullest potential, do I coat it in a layer of wax to protect the wood from the elements.You can turn your grandfather's old beater deer rifle into a beautiful firearm which will turn heads at the range or hunting camp. My service will restore and protect the wood, increasing its longevity, and vastly increasing value. A beautiful stock on an old rifle can as much as double its value compared to a dull reddish finish flaking off of a scratched and dented stock.
